Cc: Lucy Schwartz <lucyschwartz@google.com>
Subject: Peabody Museum of Natural History x Google Cultural Institute
Hi Jonathan,
I am including below more information about what it entails to join the Cultural Institute, though as mentioned earlier, we can definitely discuss further over the phone!
When a partner joins the Cultural Institute, we ask that they launch their collection with a minimum of 50 items, which can be images, audio files, or videos that meet these supported media requirements. We would be in touch throughout this process to answer any questions about how to prepare your items to be uploaded.
After the items have been uploaded, we ask partners to create a minimum of 1 digital exhibit about the items in your collection. Please find here and here examples of exhibits currently on the Cultural Institute that incorporate many of the features the exhibit tool offers. If of interest, you can embed your exhibit back onto your website after it has launched, like this partner has done.
We would be thrilled to explore capturing 360 panoramas of the museum with our Street View technology! This would allow viewers to take a virtual tour of the museum and the imagery could easily be translated into curated virtual tours that can be viewed on the Cultural Institute or more immersively on Google’s Virtual Reality device Cardboard. Additionally, the Street View imagery can be used in virtual fieldtrips for classrooms, known as Expeditions.
I have a draft of the partnership agreement for your reference. We can send the final version of the agreement if you could kindly confirm the legal name and address of the institution, and the name, title, and email address of the signatory.
Thank you, and I look forward to speaking with you more.
Best,
Jamie

From: peabody.allstaff-bounces@mailman.yale.edu [mailto:peabody.allstaff-bounces@mailman.yale.edu] On Behalf Of Melien, Andrew
Sent: Tuesday, January 10, 2017 1:27 PM
To: peabody.allstaff@mailman.yale.edu
Cc: peabody.curators@mailman.yale.edu
Subject: Introduction and hello
It’s been great meeting many of you, and I’m very excited to join YPM’s team as your new Digital Media Specialist.
A little bit about myself: My background is in electronic media, arts, and communication. On a day-to-day basis, I’m a multimedia designer and web developer, but this really means that I can (and do) enjoy working on projects that span far and wide. I’ve worked with many types of software and multimedia types, including databases, charts and data visualization, website and web app development, graphic design and illustration, motion graphics and special effects, audio and video production, 3D modeling/animation and more. In a past life, I was a UI/UX designer and technical product manager for an environmental data/mapping company, so data presentation and visual communication are some of my strong points.
That being said, I expect to be working closely with many of you on a variety of projects, so I hope this brief summary of myself gives you an idea of what kind of tasks I can collaborate with you on. I’m looking forward to meeting everyone and learning about the roles you all play for the Museum during the upcoming weeks, and I am more than happy to schedule something with anyone who would like to chat about your general digital needs and items in your pipelines. Please don’t hesitate to call, email, or stop by.
Hope to see you soon!
Andy
Andy Melien
Digital Media Specialist
